clarkware wrote:

&gt; --- In junit@y..., Mike Clark &lt;mike@c...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Depending on the implementation of the singleton you&#39;re attempting
&gt; to test, it
&gt; &gt; may be possible to obtain a reference to its sole instance (or
&gt; instances) and
&gt; &gt; assign it a null value.  If the implementation uses lazy
&gt; initialization, this
&gt; &gt; may trigger reinitialization on the next invocation of
&gt; getInstance().
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; Correction.  Of course the following will not work:
&gt;
&gt;     Object o = getInstance(...);
&gt;     o = null;
&gt;
&gt; The reference to &#39;o&#39; is a copy, so assigning it &#39;null&#39; will have no
&gt; effect on the singleton.  The only way to assign a &#39;null&#39; value is
&gt; through a setter on the singleton itself.
